Even More Linear Regression

Dr Christopher Yau

17/10/2017

Estimating confidence intervals for linear models

Consider a linear model of the form: \[ y_i = a + bx_i + \epsilon_i \] where \(a\) is an intercept, \(b\) is a slope term and \(\epsilon \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\) is normally distributed noise with variance \(\sigma^2\).

Lets use R to simulate some data:

library(ggplot2)

a = -1
b = 0.5
sigma2 = 0.1
n = 100

x = rnorm(n, 0, 1)
e = rnorm(n, 0, sqrt(sigma2))
y = a + b*x + e

Now lets fit a linear model and compute the predictions:

dat = data.frame(x=x, y=y)
fit = lm(y~x, dat)

a_hat = fit$coefficients[1]
b_hat = fit$coefficients[2]

dat$y_hat = a_hat + b_hat*x

Check the fit to see if it is OK:

plt = ggplot(dat, aes(x=x, y=y))
plt = plt + geom_point()
plt = plt + geom_line(aes(x=x, y=y_hat), colour="red")
print(plt)

We now want to estimate a 95% confidence interval for the slope parameter \(b\). Remember, the 95% confidence interval is an interval that contains the true value of \(b\) (0.5) in 95% of experiments if we were able to repeat the experiments over and over.

Theory tells us that the sampling distribution for the slope parameter is centred on the true value of \(b\) (as the estimator is unbiased) and has an estimated variance of the form: \[ \hat{\sigma}_{\hat{b}}^2 = s^2 \frac{n}{n S_{xx} - S_x^2} \] where the \(S\)-terms denotes sums: \[ \begin{align} S_{xx} &= \sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2, \\ S_x &= \sum_{i=1}^n x_i \end{align} \] (see pp.99 of your primer document). The quantity \(s^2\) is simply the estimated noise variance (unbiased version): \[ s^2 = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1} (y_i - \hat{a} - \hat{b} x_i)^2 \] The square root of \(\hat{\sigma}_{\hat{b}}\) is known as the standard error of the slope estimator.

Lets compute this for our data:

Sxx = sum(x^2)
Sx = sum(x)

s2 = var(y - fit$fitted.values)

sigma_b_hat = sqrt(s2)*sqrt(n/(n*Sxx-Sx^2)) 
print(sigma_b_hat)
## [1] 0.03038421

This is the standard error of the slope estimate for our data.

For large samples, theory tells us that the confidence interval for \(b\) is given by: \[ \hat{b} \pm z_{\alpha/2} \hat{\sigma}_{\hat{b}} \] where \(z_{\alpha/2}\) is an ordinate of the standard normal distribution for the desired significance level. In this case, we want a 95% confidence interval so we require \(\alpha = 1-0.95 = 0.05\) or \(z_{0.025} = -1.96\).

Now, lets compute our confidence interval for our data:

z = qnorm((1-0.95)/2)
b_conf_int = c( b_hat + z*sigma_b_hat, b_hat - z*sigma_b_hat  )

print(b_conf_int)
##         x         x 
## 0.4914107 0.6105146

Deriving the confidence interval by simulation

Lets check if the theory is correct using simulations. Lets write a loop to simulate 10,000 data sets (we will keep the same \(x\)s) and fit a linear model each time to get estimates of the slope parameter:

n_its = 10000 # number of loops
b_hat_all = rep(0, n_its) # store my slope estimates here
for ( it in 1:n_its ){
  e = rnorm(n, 0, sqrt(sigma2)) # generate noise
  y_new = a + b*x + e # compute y's
  dat = data.frame(x=x, y=y_new) # set up data frame
  fit_new = lm(y~x, dat) # fit lm
  b_hat = fit_new$coefficients[2] # extract slope parameter estimate
  b_hat_all[it] = b_hat # store
}

Lets draw a histogram of the slope estimates:

hist(b_hat_all, 30)

print(mean(b_hat_all))
## [1] 0.4998268
print(sd(b_hat_all))
## [1] 0.03268663

It is normally distributed with mean 0.5 and standard deviation 0.032 is close to what we computed above for the standard error \(\hat{\sigma}_{\hat{b}}\)! The sampling distribution of \(b\) does seem to fit the theory!

Now, lets think about the confidence intervals. First, set up a vector to consider a range of confidence interval widths. We will use 100 widths between 0.5 and 2 times the standard deviation of the slope parameters I have estimated:

widths = seq(from=0.5, to=2.0, length=100)*sd(b_hat_all)
n_widths = length(widths)

Now, for each width, I am going to create an interval centred on the values of \(\hat{b}\) I have computed and count how many times in those 10,000 simulations the true value of \(b\) (0.5) falls in that interval:

contained_in_interval = rep(0, n_widths)
for ( wi in 1:n_widths) {
  interval_width = widths[wi]
  lower_limit = b_hat_all-interval_width # lower limit of interval
  upper_limit = b_hat_all+interval_width # upper limit of interval
  contained_in_interval[wi] = sum( ( lower_limit < b ) & ( upper_limit > b ) ) # is the true value in the interval? how many?
}

Now, lets plot the frequency with which each confidence interval width contains the true values

plot( widths, contained_in_interval/n_its )

What is the 95% confidence intervals width? What was that value of \(z_{\alpha/2} \hat{\sigma}_{\hat{b}}\) again?

print(abs(z*sigma_b_hat))
## [1] 0.05955196

Of course, we could have done this all using Rs built-in function confint!

confint(fit, level=0.95)
##                  2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) -1.1322143 -1.013333
## x            0.4903593  0.611566
